<subSubSection id="C363652AD179FFC9688A2F53FD45FDBE" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="429" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D179FFCB688A2F53FBBAFACB" blockId="8.[166,1225,1217,1852]" box="[219,1149,1313,1340]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">
T y p e l o c a l i t y. 
<location id="8EA6607AD179FFCB69E62F50FDAFFACB" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03D087B7D179FFC968F72EF0FD45FDBE:8EA6607AD179FFCB69E62F50FDAFFACB" box="[439,616,1313,1340]" country="Denmark" name="Skaerum MOlle" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" stateProvince="Jutland">Skaerum MØlle</location>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49BDF843D179FFCB6A222F50FD0CFACC" box="[627,715,1313,1339]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Jutland</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D179FFCB6A872F50FC81FACC" box="[726,838,1313,1339]" name="Denmark" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Denmark</collectingCountry>
(
<geoCoordinate id="EE4D5066D179FFCB6B042F50FC20FACB" box="[853,999,1313,1340]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">56.33°20' N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE4D5066D179FFCB6BA32F50FBB7FACB" box="[1010,1136,1313,1340]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">8.35°21' E</geoCoordinate>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D179FFCB688A2F30FE81FA8B" blockId="8.[166,1225,1217,1852]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">S t r a t i g r a p h i c a l r a n g e. Gram Formation, late Miocene (early-middle Tortonian, 8.0–11.5 ma).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D179FFCB688A2FF0FE7BFA4C" blockId="8.[166,1225,1217,1852]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">
Etymology. After 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB69902FF3FDCDFA6C" box="[449,522,1410,1435]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Dania</emphasis>
(Latinized, noun, feminine) — 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D179FFCB6B282FF0FC2BFA6C" box="[889,1004,1409,1435]" name="Denmark" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Denmark</collectingCountry>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB6BA72FF0FB83FA6C" authorityName="Koretsky, Rahmat et Peters" authorityYear="2014" box="[1014,1092,1409,1435]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="danica">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB6BA72FF0FB83FA6C" box="[1014,1092,1409,1435]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">danica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Latinized, adj.) — from 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D179FFCB69142FD0FE7EFA4C" box="[325,441,1441,1467]" name="Denmark" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Denmark</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D179FFCB688A2FB3FB9CF9AC" blockId="8.[166,1225,1217,1852]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">D i a g n o s i s. Coronoid and olecranon fossae of humerus wide and shallow; extended more proximally than medial epicondyle, almost reaching distal part of deltoid crest; entepicondylar foramen large, with wide bridge over it; thin lateral epicondyle very elongated, but does not reach distal part of deltoid crest; medial epicondyle wide and flattened, its lateral border forming an oval that is oriented 45° to the bone’s axis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D179FFCA688A2C13FD56F8C5" blockId="8.[166,1225,1217,1852]" lastBlockId="9.[174,1233,1560,1843]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="428" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d c o m p a r i s o n. The humeral trochlea is very pronounced, especially the capitulum. The groove between the trochlea and capitulum (the middle of the internal crest of the humeral trochlear) is flattened near the floor of the coronoid fossa, unlike that in 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB691A2CB0FE19F92C" authorityName="Trouessart" authorityYear="1897" box="[331,478,1729,1755]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Monachinae">Monachinae</taxonomicName>
(= arch-like) or Cystophorinae (= appearing wave-like over the coronoid fossa) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D179FFCB69392C90FD44F90C" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Rahmat, S. J." box="[360,643,1761,1787]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" pagination="325 - 350" refId="ref9725" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Rahmat, S. J. First record of fossil Cystophorinae (Carnivora, Phocidae): middle Miocene seals from the northern Paratethys // Revista Italiana di Paleontologia e Stratigrafia. - 2013. - 119. - P. 325 - 350." type="book chapter" year="2013">Koretsky, Rahmat, 2013</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="13422A24D179FFCB6ADA2C90FD03F90B" box="[651,708,1761,1788]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1375,1397]" captionTargetId="graphics-341@6.[660,739,1042,1092]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Gryphoca nordica sp. n., paratype, proximal part of right humerus (reversed); Gram, Jutland, Denmark. Clay pit of Gram Teglvaerk, Gram Formation (late Miocene, early-middle Tortonian, 8.0–11.5 ma); MSM 1404x1 (cast in Geological Museum, Copenhagen, Denmark): 3A — caudal; 3B — cranial; 3C — medial; 3D — lateral view. Abbreviations: ac — anconeal crest; rf — radial fossa; sg — spiral groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462211/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">fig. 3</figureCitation>
). The trochlea is higher and more prominent than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB69572D73FE45F8EC" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[262,386,1793,1819]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB69572D73FE45F8EC" box="[262,386,1793,1819]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">P. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(pl. 3, 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB698A2D70FDEDF8EC" box="[475,554,1793,1819]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">1A–1B</emphasis>
). The coronoid and olecranon fossae are so shallow (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB697C2D53FE60F8CC" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[301,423,1825,1852]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB697C2D53FEFAF8CC" box="[301,317,1826,1851]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB691D2D50FE60F8CC" box="[332,423,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) that they are barely outlined. They extend more proximal than the medial epicondyle and do not reach the distal part of the deltoid crest. The entepicondylar foramen is large, oval (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D178FFCA6A342C48FD18F9A5" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[613,735,1592,1619]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6A342C48FDB2F9A5" box="[613,629,1593,1618]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6AD52C49FD18F9A5" box="[644,735,1592,1618]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), with a broad and flat bridge over it. The lateral epicondyle is narrow, very elongated, and does not reach the distal part of the deltoid crest, but extends farther proximally than the medial epicondyle (as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D178FFCA6C5F2C08FB4EF965" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[1038,1161,1656,1683]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6C5F2C08FBD9F965" box="[1038,1054,1657,1682]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6C7F2C09FB4EF965" box="[1070,1161,1656,1682]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The medial epicondyle is oval (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D178FFCA6ADD2CE8FCC2F945" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[652,773,1688,1715]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6ADD2CE8FD5BF945" box="[652,668,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6AFB2CE9FCC2F945" box="[682,773,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and forms a 45° angle with the bone’s axis. The distal epiphysis is narrower and thinner than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D178FFCA6B3B2CC8FC21F925" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[874,998,1720,1747]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6B3B2CC8FCBDF925" box="[874,890,1721,1746]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA6BDA2CC9FC21F925" box="[907,998,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The entire bone is unusually flat, and slender. Collectively, these features lend a spatula-like appearance of the distal end of the humerus. The general appearance of the bone suggests that it belongs to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D178FFCA69742D69FE61F8C5" box="[293,422,1816,1842]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA69742D69FE61F8C5" box="[293,422,1816,1842]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">Platyphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as indicated above.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF066629D178FFCA68FF2EF3FEACFA8A" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462213" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6462213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462213/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" startId="9.[174,222,1154,1176]" subCaptionStartIDs="9.[174,207,1180,1202] 9.[511,538,1207,1229]" subCaptionStarts="Fig. 1 &amp; fig. 2 E" targetBox="[332,1066,174,1125]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D178FFCA68FF2EF3FF33FB6F" blockId="9.[174,1232,1154,1229]" box="[174,244,1154,1176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">Plate 3.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D178FFCA68FF2EEDFB86FB3A" blockId="9.[174,1232,1154,1229]" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">
<figureCitation id="13422A24D178FFCA68FF2EEDFF22FB45" box="[174,229,1180,1202]" captionStart="Plate 1" captionStartId="3.[174,222,1510,1532]" captionTargetBox="[266,1108,462,988]" captionTargetId="figure-141@3.[266,1108,459,1496]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Plate 1. Fig. 1. Pontophoca sarmatica, right femur; Kishinev, Moldavia (Middle Miocene, middle Sarmatian); аfter Koretsky, Grigorescu (2002: fig. 3); USNM 214980: 1A — cranial; 1B — caudal view. Рис. 1. Pontophoca sarmatica, правая бедренная кость; Кишинев, Молдова (средний миоцен, средний сармат); по: Koretsky, Grigorescu (2002: рис. 3); USNM 214980: 1A — вид спереди; 1B — вид сзади." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6462207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6462207/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D178FFCA68A02EECFE6AFB45" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[241,429,1181,1202]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="428" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D178FFCA68A02EECFE6AFB45" box="[241,429,1181,1202]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="428">Platyphoca vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, distal part of left humerus. Lee CreekMine, Yorktown Formation (Pliocene, 5.0– 5.8 ma); аfter 
