</caption>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D17BFFC9688A2ADEFB8EFEBD" blockId="10.[166,1225,175,586]" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">
Discussion. Although a comparison with the humerus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D17BFFC96BCB2AC1FBD1FF3E" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[922,1046,175,202]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC96BCB2AC1FC6DFF3E" box="[922,938,176,201]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC96BEA2ADEFBD1FF3E" box="[955,1046,175,201]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is limited due to the absence of the proximal part of the bone as well as by its origin from a different geological age, this Danish humerus is compatible with humeri of 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D17BFFC96BB02A9EFB0FFEFE" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[993,1224,239,265]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC96BB02A9EFB0FFEFE" box="[993,1224,239,265]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">Platyphoca vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several anatomical characters and its size. At the same time, the preserved part of the humerus appears to bear enough distinctive characters to describe a new taxon.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D17BFFC9688A2B3EFD45FDBE" blockId="10.[166,1225,175,586]" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D17BFFC969022B3EFE04FE9E" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[339,451,335,361]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Gryphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC969022B3EFE04FE9E" box="[339,451,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">Gryphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the unusual and rare taxon 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D17BFFC96B5F2B3EFC48FE9E" box="[782,911,335,361]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC96B5F2B3EFC48FE9E" box="[782,911,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">Platyphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to researchers by name and was critically re-examined by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D17BFFC96AD02B01FCC5FE7D" author="Ray, C. E." box="[641,770,367,394]" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref10216" refString="Ray, C. E. Phoca wymani and other Tertiary seals (Mammalia: Phocidae) described from the eastern seaboard of North America // Smithsonian Contributions to Paleobiology. - 1976. - 28. - P. 1 - 36." type="book chapter" year="1976">Ray (1976)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D17BFFC96B6D2B1EFBA3FE7D" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Ray, C. E." box="[828,1124,367,394]" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" pagination="81 - 140" refId="ref9574" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Ray, C. E. Phocidae of the Pliocene of eastern USA // Geology and paleontology of the Lee Creek Mine, North Carolina IV / Eds C. E. Ray, D. A. Bohaska, I. A. Koretsky et al. - Virginia Museum of Natural History, 2008. - 15 (Special Publication). - P. 81 - 140." type="book chapter" year="2008">Koretsky and Ray (2008)</bibRefCitation>
. Despite the fragmentary representation of this species in Van Beneden’s original collection, the examination of additional fossil material from the Lee Creek Mine (
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D17BFFC96B942BDEFBC6FE3D" box="[965,1025,431,458]" name="United States of America" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">USA</collectingCountry>
) shows the same very distinctive morphological features (such as spatula-like distal end of the humerus). The high affinity of this newly described humerus from 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D17BFFC96B672B9EFC61FDFE" box="[822,934,495,521]" name="Denmark" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">Denmark</collectingCountry>
with 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D17BFFC96BB82B9EFBADFDFE" box="[1001,1130,495,521]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC96BB82B9EFBADFDFE" box="[1001,1130,495,521]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">Platyphoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the amount of similar fossil material from other parts of the world indicate that 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D17BFFC96C19287EFF33FDBE" authorityName="Koretsky &amp; Rahmat &amp; Peters" authorityYear="2014" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="10" pageNumber="429" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="danica">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D17BFFC96C19287EFF33FDBE" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="429">Platyphoca danica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents an identifiable species.
</paragraph>
